description: From Middle English caboche, cabage (“cabbage”; “a certain fish”), a borrowing from Anglo-Norman caboche (“head”), a northern variant of caboce, of uncertain origin. Some authorities derive it from Latin caput (“head”), others from ca- (said to be an expressive prefix) + boce (“hump; bump”)..

entries.meaning: An edible plant (Brassica oleracea var. capitata) having a head of green leaves.
(uncountable) The leaves of this plant eaten as a vegetable.
(countable, offensive) A person with severely reduced mental capacities due to brain damage.
examples: After the car crash, he became a cabbage.

entries.meaning: Used as a term of endearment.
(uncountable, slang) Marijuana leaf, the part that is not smoked but from which cannabutter can be extracted.
The terminal bud of certain palm trees, used for food.
The cabbage palmetto (Sabal palmetto), a palm of the southeastern US coasts and nearby islands.

verbs.description: cabbage (third-person singular simple present cabbages, present participle cabbaging, simple past and past participle cabbaged)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To form a head like that of the cabbage.
(intransitive, slang) To do nothing; to idle; veg out.

description: Unclear. Perhaps from Dutch *kabbassen, from Old French cabasser (“put into a basket”), from cabas. Alternatively, perhaps from an earlier word *carbage (“shred”), a potential variant of *garbage (“wheat straw”).

entries.meaning: (uncountable, slang) Scraps of cloth which are left after a garment has been cut out, which tailors traditionally kept.

verbs.description: cabbage (third-person singular simple present cabbages, present participle cabbaging, simple past and past participle cabbaged)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To purloin or embezzle; to pilfer, to steal.
examples: Your tailor […] cabbages whole yards of cloth.
